To penalize genes which are further from the peak of TTTPs, the distance between the age of turning point (
A g
) and the target age (
T
) is used as the exponent in an exponential expression with base 1.5. This function gives greatest emphasis to genes with D = 0, with a rapid fall over neighbouring years such that a human gene with D = 6 years have scores 9% the size of those with equivalent pre-turn changes in expression level at D = 0. The scoring function is graphically depicted in Figure 1—figure supplement 1. We show in Figure 5—figure supplement 5 that the results are stable to variation in the exponent base.
